An n-gene Boolean network is defined by a set of binary variables V={X1,X2,..,Xn}, and a set of Boolean functions F={f1,f2,…,fn}, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{i}\!:\{0,1\}^{k_{i}}\rightarrow \{0,1\}$\end{document}fi:{0,1}ki→{0,1} determines the value of gene Xi when it has ki regulating genes. The transition rule X(t+1)=F(X(t)) governs the evolution of states over time. In a Boolean network with perturbation (BNp), each gene may flip its value with a small perturbation probability p. In this network, the next state at time t+1 is F(X(t)) with probability (1−p)n or F(X(t))⊕γ with probability 1−(1−p)n, where γ is a binary vector of size n and ⊕ is the component-wise addition modulo 2 operator. The underlying state evolution of a BNp over time can be viewed as a Markov chain with a transition probability matrix P. The TPM can be derived using the regulatory structure of the network and the perturbation probability [22]. When p > 0 the Markov chain is guaranteed to possess a unique steady-state distribution π.

